        {
          "title": "One Battle After Another",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "No. 1 today, though Sean stresses that's not a winner call: an Oppenheimer or a Shakespeare in Love path both leave it at 1 or 2."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hamnet",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Holds at 2 on the back of its Toronto People's Choice win."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sinners",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Bumped to 3 after listener pushback; the knock is timing (April) and Academy taste, not quality."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sentimental Value",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Slid to 4. A real wow at festivals, but it didn't hit as hard over the fall."
        },
        {
          "title": "Jay Kelly",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Got a bounce from its New York Film Festival home game; a Fellini-esque, filmmaker's Baumbach."
        },
        {
          "title": "It Was Just an Accident",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The Palme d'Or winner and France's international-feature entry, close to an automatic."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bugonia",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Lanthimos and Emma Stone, plus a touted Jesse Plemons turn; sneaks in at 7."
        },
        {
          "title": "A House of Dynamite",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Both were mixed on it, but Bigelow's tension-cranking and its it-speaks-to-the-moment lightness may play in its favor."
        },
        {
          "title": "Frankenstein",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "New to the list after finishing second at Toronto; the Academy loves del Toro and Netflix gets nominations."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wicked for Good",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Kept on faith. Big fanbase, no heat yet, and the campaign hasn't started."
